The following two examples fail with current `nightly`: `cannot infer type of the type parameter A...` or `type annotations needed`, respectively:
```rust
#![feature(default_type_parameter_fallback)]

pub fn empty_vec<A=u32>() -> Vec<A> {
    Vec::new()
}

pub fn use_empty_vec() {
    empty_vec();
}
```

```rust
#![feature(default_type_parameter_fallback)]

use core::marker::PhantomData;

pub struct WithTypeDefault<T = ()> {
    field: PhantomData<T>
}

impl <T> WithTypeDefault<T> {
    pub fn to_t(&self) -> T {
        loop {}
    }
}

pub fn use_to_t() {
    let with_type_default = WithTypeDefault {field: PhantomData {} };
    let to_t = with_type_default.to_t();
}
```

Regarding the motivation to solve this issue, here's an example of code using the common builder pattern that seems like it should compile, but does not because of this.

The ergonomics of forcing the caller to specify the types of the fields not set are just horrible.  It entirely defeats the purpose of using the builder pattern.  So the only practical workaround is to use boxing and dynamic dispatch (which itself is not always possible because of object safety).

```rust
use std::future::Future;

type DefaultFuture = std::future::Pending<()>;

pub struct Builder<F1 = DefaultFuture, F2 = DefaultFuture> {
    fut1: Option<F1>,
    fut2: Option<F2>,
}

impl<F1, F2> Builder<F1, F2>
where
  F1: Future<Output = ()>,
  F2: Future<Output = ()>,
{
    pub fn new() -> Self {
        Self { fut1: None, fut2: None }
    }

    pub fn with_fut1(mut self, f: F1) -> Self {
        self.fut1 = Some(f);
        self
    }

    pub fn with_fut2(mut self, f: F2) -> Self {
        self.fut2 = Some(f);
        self
    }

    pub fn build(self) -> () {
        todo!()
    }
}

fn main() {
    let _foo = Builder::new()
        //.with_fut1(async move {}) // It should be optional to set this.
        .with_fut2(async move {})
        .build();
    // But it's not...
    // Error: cannot infer type of the type parameter `F1` declared on the struct `Builder`
}
```

